The '''2023 season''' was the '''[[Castleford Tigers]]'''' 98th season in the [[Rugby Football League]] and their 16th consecutive season in the top flight of [[Rugby league in England|English rugby league]]. The club competed in the [[2023 Super League season|2023 Super League]] and the [[2023 Challenge Cup]].

Castleford began the season under head coach [[Lee Radford]], before he was sacked in March and replaced by his assistant [[Andy Last]]. Last himself was dismissed after five months in charge, with [[Danny Ward (rugby league)|Danny Ward]] appointed for the remainder of the campaign. The team was captained by [[Paul McShane (rugby league)|Paul McShane]], with [[Joe Westerman]] as interim in his absence. They finished the Super League season in 11th place, narrowly surviving a relegation battle with [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]].

== Season overview ==
Having finished the [[2022 Castleford Tigers season|2022 season]] in 7th place, falling short of play-off qualification on the final day, Castleford recruited high-profile signings including [[Gareth Widdop]], [[Jacob Miller (rugby league)|Jacob Miller]] and [[Albert Vete]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wellens |first=Megan |date=16 February 2023 |title=Super League 2023: Meet the teams part one |url=https://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/13995/12806788/super-league-2023-meet-the-teams-part-one |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Going into [[Lee Radford]]'s second year as head coach, expectations were mixed:<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 January 2023 |title=2023 season preview: Castleford Tigers |url=https://www.superleague.co.uk/article/3241/2023-season-preview-castleford-tigers |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Super League}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Gordon |first=James |date=15 February 2023 |title=The favourites to win Super League, Challenge Cup, Man of Steel, top try scorer and relegation odds |url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/post/the-favourites-to-win-super-league-challenge-cup-man-of-steel-top-try-scorer-and-relegation-odds |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Love Rugby League}}</ref> a new-look spine was an enticing prospect,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darbyshire |first=Drew |date=8 February 2023 |title=We should be challenging: Joe Westerman predicts big year for Castleford |url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/post/we-should-be-challenging-joe-westerman-predicts-big-year-for-castleford |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Love Rugby League}}</ref> however the Tigers squad also had the league's highest average age.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pattison |first=Cam |date=28 January 2023 |title=The average age of every Super League club's first choice 13 |url=https://www.seriousaboutrl.com/the-average-age-of-every-super-league-clubs-first-choice-13-67276/ |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Serious About Rugby League}}</ref>

Pre-season preparations were beset by coaching absences and disorganised, leaving the team on the back foot according to senior players [[Jordan Turner]] and [[Kenny Edwards (rugby league)|Kenny Edwards]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Callum |date=16 January 2024 |title=From a pre-season "shambles" to speaking out on issues: Jordan Turner bares all on "toughest year" of his career with Castleford Tigers |url=https://www.totalrl.com/from-a-pre-season-shambles-to-speaking-out-on-issues-jordan-turner-bares-all-on-toughest-year-of-his-career-with-castleford-tigers/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=TotalRL}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Callum |date=8 November 2023 |title=Kenny Edwards explains how Castleford Tigers' demise began before the 2023 Super League season and why it was the "toughest year" of his career |url=https://www.totalrl.com/kenny-edwards-explains-how-castleford-tigers-demise-began-before-the-2023-super-league-season-and-why-it-was-the-toughest-year-of-his-career/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=TotalRL}}</ref> In a poor start to the season, Castleford fell to defeats against [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]] and [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]]. A heavy loss to [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] in round 3 proved a tipping point, with Radford relieved of his first-team duties on 6 March.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Newsum |first=Matt |date=6 March 2023 |title=Lee Radford: Castleford Tigers coach leaves Super League club by mutual agreement |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/64861536 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=6 March 2023 |title=Club statement: Lee Radford |url=https://castlefordtigers.com/article.php?id=8501 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Castleford Tigers}}</ref> Assistant coach [[Andy Last]] took charge of the team on an interim basis, while the club began a recruitment process for a permanent successor.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shaw |first=Matthew |date=4 April 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers interview head coach applicants as Andy Last looks to convince hierarchy |url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/castleford-tigers-interview-head-coach-26632860 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Yorkshire Live}}</ref> Centre [[Jake Mamo]] also departed the squad on 15 March after announcing his retirement.

The Tigers registered their first win of the season in round 5 against the [[Leeds Rhinos]], in between miserable losses to [[Huddersfield Giants|Huddersfield]] and [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]]. After a further defeat away to [[Catalans Dragons|Catalans]], they secured a Rivals Round victory over [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]]. On 19 April, after overseeing two wins from six matches in charge, Last was appointed full-time head coach on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 April 2023 |title=Andy Last: Castleford name England assistant as head coach after interim stint |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/65327804 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Castleford came close against [[Salford Red Devils|Salford]] and [[Hull KR]], but ultimately entered into a six-match losing streak, including elimination from the [[2023 Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]] at the first time of asking in front of a decade-low home crowd.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shaw |first=Matthew |date=22 May 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers break unwanted record with worrying attendance for Challenge Cup exit |url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/castleford-tigers-unwanted-record-attendance-26966409 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Yorkshire Live}}</ref> In May, [[Craig Lingard]] was appointed as an assistant coach to Last.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 May 2023 |title=Craig Lingard: Batley Bulldogs coach named Castleford Tigers assistant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/65533968 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

The [[Magic Weekend#2023: Newcastle|Magic Weekend]] provided the occasion of their third victory, with [[Jason Qareqare|Qareqare]]'s try and [[Gareth Widdop|Widdop]]'s conversion completing a comeback over [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]]. A large loss to [[Salford Red Devils|Salford]] followed, with captain [[Paul McShane (rugby league)|Paul McShane]]'s season ended by a fractured forearm,<ref>{{Cite web |last=McAllister |first=Josh |date=13 June 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers suffer major blow with Paul McShane timeframe revealed plus update on alternative options, including Jacques O'Neill |url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/post/castleford-tigers-suffer-major-blow-with-paul-mcshane-timeframe-revealed-plus-update-on-alternative-options-including-jacques-oneill |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Love Rugby League}}</ref> although the Tigers consolidated with a win over out-of-form [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]]. Positioned 11th in the table and with bottom placed [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]] picking up form, another lengthy losing streak began to build up the pressure on Castleford.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Callum |date=10 July 2023 |title=Andy Last's honest view on Castleford Tigers relegation scrap with Wakefield Trinity |url=https://www.totalrl.com/andy-lasts-honest-view-on-castleford-tigers-relegation-scrap-with-wakefield-trinity/ |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=TotalRL}}</ref> A host of signings, including [[Liam Horne]], [[Charbel Tasipale]] and [[Blake Austin]], aimed to turn the tide back in Cas' favour<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Brien |first=James |date=3 August 2023 |title='Big bonus for us': Castleford Tigers confirm signing of Leeds Rhinos half-back Blake Austin in sensational swoop |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/big-bonus-for-us-castleford-tigers-confirm-signing-of-leeds-rhinos-half-back-blake-austin-in-sensational-swoop-4242115 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=The Yorkshire Post}}</ref> - however, on 4 August, a comprehensive loss against [[Huddersfield Giants|Huddersfield]] sent the Tigers bottom on points difference, with a number of fans staging a protest.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 August 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers fans stage protest after loss to Huddersfield Giants |url=https://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/rugby-league/12933925/castleford-tigers-fans-stage-protest-after-loss-to-huddersfield-giants |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Walker |first=Callum |date=4 August 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers fans refuse to leave stadium in protest following dismal Super League loss |url=https://www.totalrl.com/castleford-tigers-fans-refuse-to-leave-stadium-in-protest-following-dismal-super-league-loss/ |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=TotalRL}}</ref> That evening, the club announced that Last would depart with immediate effect.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 August 2023 |title=Andy Last: Castleford Tigers sack head coach after falling to bottom of Super League |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/66412788 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=5 August 2023 |title=Andy Last: Castleford Tigers head coach sacked following 28-0 home defeat to Huddersfield Giants |url=https://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12204/12933921/andy-last-castleford-tigers-head-coach-sacked-following-28-0-home-defeat-to-huddersfield-giants |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> 

On 9 August, Castleford confirmed the appointment of [[Danny Ward (rugby league)|Danny Ward]] as head coach on a deal until the end of the season, with [[Dane Dorahy]] joining as an assistant.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 August 2023 |title=Danny Ward: Castleford Tigers appoint former London coach until end of season |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/66455512 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=9 August 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers: Danny Ward unveiled as head coach until end of season following Andy Last's departure |url=https://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12204/12936796/castleford-tigers-danny-ward-unveiled-as-head-coach-until-end-of-season-following-andy-lasts-departure |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> The first fixture under the new staff saw a huge clash away at relegation rivals [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]], billed as the repeat of the 2006 'Battle of [[Belle Vue (Wakefield)|Belle Vue]]'.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bazeley |first=Marc |date=18 August 2023 |title=Danny Ward: Castleford Tigers head coach aims to avoid history repeating ahead of key Wakefield Trinity clash |url=https://www.skysports.com/rugby-league/news/12196/12941287/danny-ward-castleford-tigers-head-coach-aims-to-avoid-history-repeating-ahead-of-key-wakefield-trinity-clash |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> The Tigers started as underdogs<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shaw |first=Matthew |date=18 August 2023 |title=Bookmakers deliver verdict on Wakefield Trinity and Castleford Tigers showdown |url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/bookmakers-deliver-verdict-wakefield-trinity-27547219 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Yorkshire Live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shaw |first=Matthew |date=18 August 2023 |title=Pundits unanimous on outcome of Wakefield Trinity and Castleford Tigers battle |url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/pundits-unanimous-outcome-wakefield-trinity-27547673 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Yorkshire Live}}</ref> but fought to a vital 28–12 victory, with [[Greg Eden]] scoring a [[hat-trick]]. Now with the upper hand, a win against [[Hull F.C.|Hull FC]] in Castleford's final home game all but guaranteed survival.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Heppenstall |first=Ross |date=9 September 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers in dreamland as difference-maker Danny Ward underlines credentials and Wakefield Trinity face up to grim reality |url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/post/castleford-tigers-in-dreamland-as-difference-maker-danny-ward-underlines-credentials-and-wakefield-trinity-face-up-to-grim-reality |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Love Rugby League}}</ref> Despite sustaining extremely heavy defeats against [[Warrington Wolves|Warrington]], [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] and [[Leeds Rhinos|Leeds]] in the closing rounds, Castleford confirmed an 11th-placed finish,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Newsum |first=Matt |date=15 September 2023 |title=Wakefield Trinity relegated after 24 years in Super League following Leigh loss |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/66797544 |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> consigning [[Wakefield Trinity|Wakefield]] to the [[RFL Championship|Championship]] and bringing a close to a disastrous and disappointing season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Olawumi |first=Ben |date=22 September 2023 |title=Castleford Tigers ace Alex Mellor delivers brutally honest assessment of 'awful' season; 'We've massively underperformed' |url=https://www.loverugbyleague.com/post/castleford-tigers-ace-alex-mellor-delivers-brutally-honest-assessment-of-awful-season-weve-massively |access-date=24 November 2023 |website=Love Rugby League}}</ref> [[Joe Westerman]] was named both Castleford Player of the Year and Players' Player of the Year, and [[Jason Qareqare]] won a third consecutive Try of the Season award.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 September 2023 |title=Tigers host end of season dinner |url=https://castlefordtigers.com/article.php?id=8761 |access-date=12 January 2025 |website=Castleford Tigers}}</ref>

